# One in four over 25 lives with diabetes or pre-diabetes
The number of Australians impacted by diabetes is underestimated. One in four
Australians over the age of 25 lives with diabetes or pre-diabetes. If you add
to that number the family, friends and carers who support them, you have a
more accurate picture of the effect diabetes is having on the community.
Diabetes is one of the fastest growing chronic health conditions in Australia,
and to mark World Diabetes Day on 14 November, Diabetes NSW & ACT has released
There are 447,000 people living with diabetes in NSW and the ACT, and about
386,000 live with type 2 diabetes. In addition, it’s estimated there are
another 190,000 who have type 2 diabetes but are yet to be diagnosed. There
are also more than 14,500 women who have been diagnosed with gestational
Diabetes NSW & ACT CEO, Sturt Eastwood said, “Diabetes is a complex condition
“You can’t underestimate the role families’ play in helping people maintain
good health. Everyone from mums and dads to grandparents, brothers and sisters
to friends, health professionals, teachers, co-workers, researchers and
volunteers all play a role in helping to detect, prevent and care for people
Early diagnosis and treatment of diabetes is key to helping prevent or delay
life-threatening complications. If type 1 diabetes is not detected early, it
can be fatal. A delayed diagnosis of type 2 diabetes can lead to complications
such as blindness, amputation, kidney or heart disease, and depression or
“Knowing the signs of diabetes can help protect your family,” Mr Eastwood
“That’s why we’re encouraging everyone to be on the lookout for symptoms such
as sudden weight loss, tiredness or excessive thirst and urination. We’re also
encouraging anyone over 40 to include a diabetes test in their annual check-
“Type 2 is more difficult to pick because the symptoms can be mild, which
“For those with a loved one living with type 2 diabetes, supporting the
changes they need to make to their diet and exercise routine can make all the
difference to help them live well and avoid serious complications,” Mr
